Sr. in answer to yd of 6: curitt shall send the cloathes of mr. peeters to you
haveino wrott to Brussels to have the approbation of the other brother
concerdied, & shall remitt you what I am in cask for them, because
I long to be seven with them, which is allatt present fro
@ 23 ditto
London michiel peeters
mons. in antwoort aende ul van 6 & 8 deser sal de lakens op packen ende nae
London aen mr slaughter senden, ende aen hem op leggen voor soo veel als ick
schuldigh sal sijn, daer en tuschen soo m maijnart komt sal mijne voor
doen dat sij de lakens voor ul rekeninge verkoopen, ende ul goet doen
tgeene die sullen renderen, anders waer het wat ondircrectelijk gedaen
dot sijn niet voorsoo veel souden helpen naede nael het van slanghtere
goet selfs is ick scrijve en versoeke u broeders approbatie opt geene doen
en hij antwoort niet eens, sal even wel geen gelt senden sooon ick ul
ordre hebbe, ten sij ul broeder Antonion oock asprobeert daerom geelieft
hem aen te manen om met mij teffenen vant willonse sake geheel

London Abram vivian
th
S. my last to you was on the 16: curitt sence rec. boath yd of 5 & 8: curitt
the packett you desire shall be provided with all possible care & expedition
I want about 10 a 12 dayes time for itt, & 8 dayes before itt be with you will
make up the 3 weekes you bespoake & shall buy what penn worths I can
gett from Rossen, leeng you approve of what makeing: I could have withad
to know how you liked the packett N.16 because that is well of one hand
and bj which I finde more assortement then by severall others -
I shall buy non more of boinee, for other concernes I shall exspect the
acctt. of mr. Shimer: & do observe what you have don about the tayes
all which is well leaving the menagement off itt to you, I finde m..
potter the best in cloth a governo
please timely to advise mex what goods shipt aboard smith I have
accepted yd bill p. mr. Cole for £150: & past tonmy acctts I hope yd
acctt are not be hinde in yd bookes as well with them of the north, as
with mee, that so you be able to iudge & finde out, that they charge no
more on you then needfull, besides I could wish you to make shoft to pay
the bills without drawing on mee more then what you might be
in disbours for my acctt. because I would not have nother that you
should be straight nee formy share butt if you look over all you will
finde mee to have don my ut most, & haveing, much to pay shall not
be in a condition to remitt this so dages butt then I hope to be
more in cash againe whilst now I remaine with inde salues
London George Cole

Sr. in answer, to yd of 25 past I am a shamed my selfs that our pay. are so badd
butt what wonder where the people is never aday attrest the continuall allarnes
of the french keep back the sales which now wee should have much more the
mony of the standing out debts & rather then to be suspected to make uso
of other mans mony intend hence forward to go no fuither then miy
owne stock will reac to whoever that can not satisfye &cleare m
vivians acctt. butt whoever I could have you to take all things inconsideration
depends not from mee that that acctt is so
long un advisted, except I did pay all htooke the risie of the yett standing out
debts to my owne which no discreat trades man would putt mee tosthough I do
all I can to please all my correspondents & to obtaine & deserve the name
of a well meaning & endeavouring fartor, yett I studdy partticularly to make
amend & to send the ballance of the rest, which I could wish with all my heard
wasdon, intrim I doubt not butt that m. Damel vivian will allow you
the £80:-:- an acctt for ist is more then reasonable, besides mr. Depeyster
never had an attorrity to signe mr. vivians composition & for thd
orphants I may iustly pretend what is reasonable I have accepted yd bills for
acctt. of A.S. & thanck you fors yd kindness to assist him in such occasions
you may freely beleave if I could I should prevent itt with remises butt as
times are now wee know not what do lett mee do my endeavour & hope suddanmly
to cleare the acctt whilst I exspect the £80: shall pass. & rest
@ 23 Aupnst: 1681
London Arthur Hineslay
th
S. in answer to yd of 18: past & 8: curitt I hope the rest of our in ordered goods
from Exon will come with the first schip from thence of which I exspect to
have patt & acctt. bij time I observe yd complaints I am vere sensible of itt
& yett I can not help itt to bring itt out without yd complaints tradiis
brought to low with us here, so that I doubt nent yeare shall be foreed to go no
further then what my stock will reach to for nij owne, inclosed my bill for
£100:- att 35:4 att 2 uso on m. Henry Collier which please to gett accepted
& pass to yd actt. I shall do my utmost to prevent yd draught whilst I remaiine
3 if you where serve with bethtykes for returne should send you apercell for at sall
@ 23 ditto 1681
London Henry Collier
th
Sr. my last to you was on the 16: curitt lence non from your though much
be yond exspectation, because I doubted not, butt that you should have sant the acctt
of cottons before now they are with mee & I can not sell them before I know how
to governe my selfe wee are daglat allarmed by the french, which doth much
hunder our sale & keeps back on all side the mony, so that the longer, the vorse
our thinghs go I have now greater stock in trades then ever I had, yett was never
more straightned & not to much upon my actt neither & which veres mee mostes
because, I am alwayes so bare of mony as alous, & I remitt when I an & the accepted
bills I must pay & yett have now then a letter of complaints m. Anneslay
I confess hath some reason yett I finde that I can not help him to an
Aldermans estate except wee were here in a better condition, yett patience
I tought to have drawne for yd acctt. butt I would not have you complaine
neither, there fore for once the last time draw on you for my acctt £100:-
att 2 use in favour of m Anneslay, which please to accept & when dew
redraw on mee the proceed of my cloth deducted & itt shall be duely discharged the
great vorsant ende this day, sanext & wee wee are for oAH bussines againe & I rest
@ 24 ditto
Brussel Judocus De sadelaer
monsr. heb gisteren pr beurtschip aen ul gesonden in een paxken 1 D8 de 2 groene
& modecoleur spaens laken lest aen ul verkoght iet het grijs, dese drij lakens
sijn soo eel geperst & op gedaen gepackt ende met den vrapper onwonden
datter geen perijkel is die te konnen bekennen, maer ul moet daer bij tijts
in de halle voor sorge drage dat die niet en worden geopent ten sij ul daer bij is
devraght is oock maer soft de super fijne ½ brae dunne curieuse lakens
sijn ul geladen onde ick hebbe de stalen daer van ontfangen soo de selve heer
sijn sal t ul cito laten weten sij bevallen mij seer wel, soo dat niet
en twijffele ofte sullen ul seer wel dienen war mede blijve
@2 4 ditto 1681
Brussel Andries Artsens
monsr. in antwoort aenden ul van 22 deser alhoewel d'Engelsche rattienen niet
gekepert sijn soo twijffele eghter niet oft de selve sullen ul goet proffijt vendenen
ende dat ul meer vande selve sal ontbieden, soo ul present iets noodigh hadde
ick ben van alle soorte van Engelsche goederen seer wel versien
ul assignatie van hondert pattucons hebbe ick wel ontfangen als
mede de selve weirde, soo dat ick ul daer voore hebbe gecreditteert waer
moch ul voorders kan dienen gelieft te commandeeren
